<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-245-162 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 785 903</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 10 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft revamps Excel. (Microsoft Corp.'s Excel 3.0 spreadsheetsoftware) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wood, Lamont.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Excel 3.0 (Spreadsheet software) (Product introduction)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (Computerprograms).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSpreadsheets.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MICROSOFT REVAMPS EXCEL 01/10/91 REDMOND, WASHINGTON, U.S.A.andP;  1991 JAN 10(NB) -- Microsoft has announced version 3.0 of its graphics-based Excelspreadsheet, with enhancements that observers say should give its competitiona fright.andP;  The new version was simultaneously announced for Windows 3, OS/2Presentation Manager, and the Apple Macintosh.andM;More than a hundred new features were added, including an Autosum button toextract the sum of a row or column, an outliner, special help screens forLotus 1-2-3 users, and three-dimensional graphs that can be rotated on thescreen.andP;  Microsoft's new Object Linking and Embedding (OLE) protocol --through which Windows applications can be transparently called by oneanother, along with any needed data -- is also fully supported.andP;  (The onlyother package so far with OLE is PowerPoint, Microsoft's presentationgraphics package, but Microsoft's other main products use Dynamic DataExchange (DE), an earlier, simpler approach to integration.)andM;&quot;It's more graphical than any other spreadsheet to date,&quot; Tim Bajarin,executive vice president of Creative Strategies, a consulting firm in SantaClara, California, told Newsbytes.andP;  &quot;The 3-D graphics, the Autosum featureand the outliner add great depth to the concept of the spreadsheet.&quot;andM;&quot;Microsoft has been faced with the fact that Lotus has remained the premierspreadsheet, and on the word processing side WordPerfect has been the majorpackage -- but now that they have Word for Windows, Excel and PowerPointworking together (through OLE or DDE) they have a chance to break theLotus-WordPerfect stranglehold,&quot; JoAnn Stahel, president of Store BoardComputer Intelligence in Dallas, Texas, told Newsbytes.andP;  &quot;I'm a Lotus user,but I bought Excel because it as so easy to import graphics.&quot;andM;&quot;And another major consideration is that Microsoft has beaten Lotus toWindows,&quot; she added.andP;  (Lotus has a graphical version of 1-2-3 but not onebased on Windows.)andM;Other new features in Excel include drawing tools and the ability to pastegraphics from the Windows Clipboard.andP;  Users can select from 68 types ofcharts.andP;  The Macintosh version supports OLE, the first Mac software to do so.andO;The Windows version also supports the Hewlett-Packard New-Wave interface.andM;The Windows 3 version is available now and the other two versions are slatedfor &quot;the first half of 1991.&quot; Suggested U.S.andP;  pricing for each version is$495.andP;  Previous Windows users can update for $129, and the update is free toanyone who bought Excel for Windows 2.1 between Dec. 7, 1990 and April 16,1991.andP;  Mac users can update for $50.andM;French, German, Swedish, Italian, Spanish and Dutch versions of Excel arescheduled for later this year, and the new version has a feature calledInternational Macro Sheets to write macros which will work across differentlanguage versions.andM;The English version is scheduled to be sold in Canada, the United Kingdom,Sweden, Norway, Denmark, Finland, Belgium, Holland, Italy, Japan, Singapore,Hong Kong, Argentina, Chile, Malaysia, the Philippines, Indonesia, Thailandand Taiwan.andM;(Lamont Wood/19910110/Press Contact: Karen Meredith or Sarah Charf,Microsoft, 206/882-8080)</TEXT></DOC>